    <div id=learn class=section>
      <h2>Learn</h2>
      <div class=figure style="position: relative">
	<p class=caption
	   style="position: absolute; right: 0; writing-mode: vertical-rl;
		  font-size: smaller; font-style: normal">
	  <a href="https://unsplash.com/photos/cHhbULJbPwM"
	  >Photo</a>: <a href="https://unsplash.com/@crissyjarvis"
	  >Crissy Jarvis</a>
	</p>
	<p>
	  <img src="Images/crissy-jarvis-abacus.jpg"
	       alt="[Picture: an abacus]">
	</p>
      </div>
      <p>
	<a href="whatIsMathML.html" >What is MathML</a> teaches you
	how to create your first equation and to understand the base
	constructs of MathML.
      </p>
      <p>
	For a quick intro, try <a
	href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/MathML/Authoring"
	>Mozilla's tutorial</a>, <a
	href="http://danielscully.co.uk/projects/mathml-guide/"
	>Daniel Scully's Beginner's Guide</a>, or <a
	href="https://cnx.org/contents/21a1528f-c79e-4dcb-8a6b-28d958cc2b2d@1.2/Connexions_Guide_to_MathML"
	>the Connexions Guide to MathML</a>.
      </p>
      <p>
	For a thorough resource on all tags and attributes, dive into
	<a href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/MathML"
	>the excellent documentation at Mozilla</a> and you can also
	simply check out <a
	href="https://www.mathjax.org/index.html#samples" >some
	pretty examples of MathML</a>.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div id=software class=section>
      <h2>Software</h2>
      <div class=figure>
       <p>
	<img src="Home/images/BlueCalc.png"
	     alt="[Picture: a mechanical calculator bearing a W3C logo]">
       </p>
      </div>
      <p>
	Many browsers support MathML and support in math&amp;science
	applications is ubiquitous. To write MathML, you don't need
	more than a text editor, but there are
	many <a href="../wiki/Math_Tools" >tools</a> available that make it
	even easier. The MathWG keeps a non-exhaustive list on
	its <a href="../wiki/Math" >public wiki</a>,
	including <a href="../wiki/Math_Tools#Browsers" >browser
	support</a>, <a href="../wiki/Math_Tools#JavaScript_polyfills_and_browser_plugins"
	>JavaScript
	polyfills</a>, <a href="../wiki/Math_Tools#Authoring_tools"
	>authoring&amp;conversion tools</a> and more
	general <a href="../wiki/Math_Tools#Rendering" >MathML-enabled
	software</a>.
      </p>
      <p>
	Of course, nearly all software has bugs. And some programs are
	further ahead implementing MathML 3 than others.
      </p>
    </div>

