    <div id=participate class=section>
      <h2>Joining the discussion</h2>
      <p>
	The Math Working Group discusses on the
	<a href="https://lists.w3.org/Archives/Public/www-math/"
	>&lt;correc@ti.con&gt; mailing list</a>. Everybody
	can <a href="mailto:correc@ti.con?subject=subscribe"
	>subscribe</a>
	(or <a href="mailto:correc@ti.con?subject=unsubscribe"
	>unsubscribe,</a> or see <a href="../Mail/Request"
	>instructions.</a>)
      </p>
      <p>
	You can also read and create issues
	on <a href="https://github.com/mathml-refresh/mathml/issues"
	>GitHub</a>. (You need a (free) GitHub account to create a new
	issue.)
      </p>
      <p>
        The <a href="../community/mathml4/" >‘MathML Refresh’
        Community Group</a> developed drafts for MathML 4 and MathML
        Core, preparing for the Working Group. Anybody can join the
        group.
      </p>
      <!--
      <p>
       You can also join the <a href="../community/mathonwebpages/"
       >‘Getting math on Web pages’ Community Group.</a> Its work is
	to look for gaps in the <abbr title="Open Web Platform"
       >OWP</abbr> (i.e., CSS, HTML, SVG, etc.) and propose fixes to
       improve the display of math in Web pages.
      </p>
      -->
    </div>

    <div id=group class=section>
      <h2>The Math Working Group</h2>
      <p>
	The Math Working Group is one of the oldest W3C Working
	Groups. During its first period of activity
	(1996&ndash;2004), it created and maintained versions 1 and 2 of
	MathML. During its second period
	(2006&ndash;2016), it created, among other things, MathML
	version 3 and saw it become an ISO standard.
      </p>
      <p>
	Since April 2021, the group is developing a new revision of
	MathML, MathML version 4, as well as MathML Core, a subset
	that can be reliably displayed in web browsers.
      </p>
      <p class=more>
	<a href="../groups/wg/math" >Details of the Math WG&nbsp;»</a>
      </p>
    </div>



